<DOC><DOCNO> AP880914-0191 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-88 2044EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Kenya-Poachers     09-14 0141</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--Kenya-Poachers,0143</SECOND><HEAD>President Orders Park Rangers to Shoot Poachers on Sight</HEAD><DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   President Daniel arap Moi has ordered parkrangers to shoot poachers on sight, Nairobi newspapers reportedWednesday.   ``Officials should inform people about this so that innocentwananchi (people) do not loiter in the game parks and be caughtunaware,'' Moi said.   Moi's shoot-on-sight order Tuesday followed the government'ssuspension of mining and prospecting in Kenya's 53 national parksand reserves, a move aimed at stopping poachers who are decimatingthis East African nation's elephant herd.   Studies by the U.N. Environmental Program show that in the last15 years, the elephant population has dropped 85 percent in Kenya.An aerial survey in February of the vast Tsavo National Park insoutheastern Kenya found 5,363 elephants, down from an estimated35,000 in that park alone in 1974.</TEXT></DOC>